  "id": "branched-chain-amino-acid-metabolism",
  "name": "Branched-chain amino acid (BCAA) degradation",
  "category": "amino-acid-metabolism",
  "summary": "Mitochondrial catabolism of leucine, isoleucine and valine: a shared reversible transamination and an irreversible, rate-limiting BCKDH-complex decarboxylation, then three branch-specific routes yielding acetyl-CoA, acetoacetate and propionyl-CoA.",
  "description": "Branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs) — L-leucine, L-isoleucine and L-valine — are essential amino acids catabolised largely in extrahepatic mitochondria (skeletal muscle, heart, kidney, adipose, brain), while the liver, low in BCAA aminotransferase but high in the BCKDH complex, oxidises the exported branched-chain keto acids.\n\nThe pathway begins with two steps common to all three BCAAs: (1) a reversible PLP-dependent transamination by branched-chain aminotransferase (BCAT2 mitochondrial; BCAT1 cytosolic) that transfers the amino group to 2-oxoglutarate, producing glutamate and the branched-chain 2-oxo (keto) acid; and (2) an irreversible oxidative decarboxylation by the mitochondrial branched-chain α-ketoacid dehydrogenase (BCKDH) complex (E1 BCKDHA/BCKDHB, E2 DBT, E3 DLD), the committed and rate-limiting step, yielding a branched-chain acyl-CoA, CO2 and NADH. BCKDH activity is controlled by reversible phosphorylation: BCKDK phosphorylates and inactivates the E1α subunit, while the phosphatase PPM1K (PP2Cm) reactivates it; the branched-chain keto acids (notably α-ketoisocaproate) inhibit BCKDK, so a rising substrate load accelerates its own oxidation.\n\nThe three carbon skeletons then diverge. Leucine is purely **ketogenic** (isovaleryl-CoA → 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA → 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA → HMG-CoA → acetoacetate + acetyl-CoA). Valine is purely **glucogenic** (isobutyryl-CoA → methacrylyl-CoA → 3-hydroxyisobutyryl-CoA → 3-hydroxyisobutyrate → methylmalonate semialdehyde → propionyl-CoA). Isoleucine is **both** (2-methylbutyryl-CoA → tiglyl-CoA → 2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyryl-CoA → 2-methylacetoacetyl-CoA → acetyl-CoA + propionyl-CoA). The propionyl-CoA from valine and isoleucine enters the TCA cycle anaplerotically via methylmalonyl-CoA and succinyl-CoA.\n\nDefects illustrate the pathway's importance: BCKDH-complex deficiency causes maple syrup urine disease (MSUD); isovaleryl-CoA dehydrogenase (IVD) deficiency causes isovaleric acidemia; MCC, HIBCH, HSD17B10 and others underlie further inborn errors. Beyond inborn errors, elevated plasma BCAAs are among the strongest metabolomic correlates of insulin resistance and incident type 2 diabetes, and BCAA metabolism (e.g. cytosolic BCAT1 re-expression) is rewired in several cancers.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["skeletal muscle", "liver", "kidney", "heart", "adipose", "brain"],
